By Tanya Sichynsky
[https://nl.nytimes.com/f/newsletter/hJZxXOpulf9dbQwUljS5XQ~~/AAAAARA~/8yY57pb1z89c4gk683d922JbZ73Gwa9tVVknPVgGJx-Qtfrz2NmEprkvb5h0Y8s17rd_RyO_78FqwQTn4993tc9dmaPestSHQD3CUpmXIIFoHTEfA8sWGhBvTtX0u93c9ADsvhm4lkRhKFBxhUhoK3LxlIAOh-1wGnlBSUda4uW5yTLM3tI7Uk8RA6BZbb-k9ANaM_taHz1kVhRQGx71Lo9OUeHmtCw4o2xqcPU7bgfJeud5OXDR9TZgZvQC3mbRoYBBN_ywxQ7WJXKmiiOBMTi7Pcwv5pmGD2FeUBpU5GC6pJiFXwz6snFcXoC7fmuMDznyBsfx9Pk2vPj4z2cyCg~~]

At the grocery store, I am a wide-eyed baby with a wholly undeveloped sense of
object permanence. What do I have at home? Your guess is as good as mine. It
wouldn’t hurt to grab a can of beans, you know, just in case the reserves are
low.

Well, peekaboo. At present writing, there are nine cans of chickpeas in my
pantry. (There is also one can of Great Northern white beans and one can of
refried beans for good measure. I am, terrifyingly, out of black beans.)

No other ingredient lines my shelves in such quantities; chickpeas are the
linchpin of so many satisfying, delicious under-30-minute meatless meals. This
affliction — we like to call it chickpea anxiety over here
[https://nl.nytimes.com/f/newsletter/Jl76S1RyuZTJavlVKgbPYA~~/AAAAARA~/-_VOPTM6Svqli2ZaLlEQ-ECL9IdD8-vb3sr1HmNenV0c7sRBgCZB6fHBDqFANuKaQOWVhzXBzI2udWcLlOnaWAlpHXyjnSK9SSkkjXq7ztEW8PxdL-RXCsZzLosSS5gPtYnRZ6SBvJIlbu6a_Mkayf1QnLYcjdPuIvDypsoehWn0yonJu4QentNjG2hesbC0y_1Zn-YYhyD6hVmQdDgsrCVREi0N9MFLsrpFb3jLQZQ3phoVEXYAjR66HYLn6a01uxbpbI1K6ifFW3wPalyjm0KJywlB6Pz_kxfmD50h66RQjO2Uqz6DiETUkpZj5ie1i2QbwqN9MoODQ-alT89SiffYSNnzHBJWEXFjEJEMsvI~] 
— extends to many readers of The Veggie. “I do the exact same thing!” a reader
wrote me last year. “And why not other beans that can fill out a meal just as
well?”

This week, I’m taking this dilemma to the small screen (rotate that phone,
sweetie) in the latest episode of our Veggie video series. With a surplus of
chickpeas, your options range from the obvious to the unexpected.

A gif shows Tanya Sichynsky preparing a vegan Caesar salad with chickpeas.
[https://static01.nyt.com/images/2025/10/02/multimedia/02veggiegif/02veggiegif-jumbo.gif]
[https://nl.nytimes.com/f/a/i29CJRFePTMAlHibFukscg~~/AAAAARA~/ZQyWvjwAvUAoPeTcp8wdlc7R8ulH4yqfsGZVjpgHU9fDnpPgVSJ0faGbrFX7_vZdgEjrKIVI2jvd6GKGrKtTezzOHLpUlmJDGHQ2giFXc1g2FMSPe5dp9Ex5Q27kP_iAg_BjyGj7J-TrjwM7wH9_t9sfjZfiB9hRipuIuZ8dfluBmPqP8O3_Fyo5zzWOqdphj6pVxljC68yvPmL-pE_cfZHaOMmj69BfVkgNnPRJOKj9loG0qTZixBRZEDzB8j7OfjLR2-w-nq8PXLkw7YEU03mCXIJH7dyaLV31xpd4nzOrwM3CzA1ZIIM920UxGCpbfpwF5OWGGnpt6VsPL8_KTQ~~]
Put some crispy chickpeas on your salad. You’ll be glad you did.New York Times
CookingWATCH THE VIDEO →
[HTTPS://NL.NYTIMES.COM/F/A/I29CJRFEPTMALHIBFUKSCG~~/AAAAARA~/ZQYWVJWAVUAOPETCP8WDLC7R8ULH4YQFSGZVJPGHU9FDNPPGVSJ0FAGBRFX7_VZDGEJRKIVI2JVD6GKGRKTTEZZOHLPULMJDGHQ2GIFXC1G2FMSPE5DP9EX5Q27KP_IAG_BJYGJ7J-TRJWM7WH9_T9SFJZFIB9HRIPUIUZ8DFLUBMPQP8O3_FYO5ZZWOQDPHJ6PVXLJC68YVPML-PE_CFZHAOMMJ69BFVKGNNPRJOKJ9LOG0QTZIXBRZEDZB8J7OFJLR2-W-NQ8PXLKW7YEU03MCXIJH7DYALV31XPD4NZORWM3CZA1ZIIM920UXGCPBFPWF5OWGGNPT6VSPL8_KTQ~~]
I have a few suggestions, of course. Sheela Prakash’s roasted chickpeas
[https://nl.nytimes.com/f/cooking/5o1PyGEFFSdrn5Rpw1dt_A~~/AAAAARA~/Gd-Lxy4zznT8I3Toxb7bmwJ8gI9JUHg0nF7YbstfQU8BRhW29XhEuy1Lcg7xu6NcZBRsWpuUWyITuXIW3Q0Uchp850WeUSNTff5phL3qu-9LQyUv40yIP58CQT1oVKTNbhp5P-UoDwguadGgM4yg0xk0e7ezvLJnToo5EYvoEWvUJNhv3WZAt_POjUBJJv2gXC4sh0sA2l0eye2BW3ZNXgUDnku0DQ_zRP4nQx0_AdVDt_P5rICWhp2rILuugoQ1ns6POAZMi0cz6R9x3gPAndnscyMlzdvLXejZkKZ0ZvpP4RsZ4F5lSiQxj5Zz0AeqkCi5cRiSLolumVBu-epuaN6qWCjwtcNw6dQruGCEbt8~] 
make a great snack out of the oven, or use them to top Becky Hughes’s vegan
Caesar salad
[https://nl.nytimes.com/f/cooking/wzEIgC_sfGl5LDOLBpfd_Q~~/AAAAARA~/ylxy7WREEpU_xqiN2lqzy_5tVmXfRtOx16AVgS2SZDu5j_JCFpdu4potRIWd2Bk95tdBdLHrE6RiY8Dz1hSt_aBIosrQLyl0eEaOya5GTyTlUyBV175t7ZSCC89sNBgZ77w5eHUzRjcJL1F0tXa1xHaywK_-ZKzM0V6-jTnWzwgvnFomy69s83elaYNAKoxO8Y6FqNRdatsIyk-MykTky77ga5wivWERfGKiZravfywjv7Bs31zGGEP84sZY-vrTeJF2szI3PZvV7d-0vOZ3cUAt2fYEU7ZJIEtKUZlS05_tWj5Tv8EItVAa2f1RjL18AT8kdTucrTfy0DQGJA_tZhpTNUgGGpc_ifB-H_W0BsIwk4UB6dQaSGtDahEyI-jCfMatmSEzATV0XYcuNnvBbg~~]
. Having roasted chickpeas handy will shave a good 10 minutes off your cook
time. Time is money! And money is for buying more chickpeas, evidently.

I could eat Kenji López-Alt’s marinated chickpeas
[https://nl.nytimes.com/f/cooking/_0xjZs5-cu_JNiUaqN-0_Q~~/AAAAARA~/-_VOPTM6Svqli2ZaLlEQ-NOV_vn3b5skqxOqyjTivopgmBXnFOYvX7_ugRJEMeWvePyUJpDCcg2Q7WK_2jcxmH9RRe0imt0H5S79j2B7fItjXW774LwmW1Wtm88tKsdR5mi2yOrvtZDP81A2Pt1jIzOHYw73jZbXR7iUlsQ9AC0rxNavMpVuD47slbRQ_pzwWktrd3hene9CfY9ZbAYtK6Jg8xlezByzva2EyoNM0JQ29QyqM1wwrCDXa2qdoxK9H84MAKuTivQOzd5t2g6Dd_XEADX5DvnxftRmP_CSXjgQGDpkE2x0790vP3gGPFBA6p66VdXf4iQgei2RB-8rTEo6pbsOv9k_uZo8vkgMDtg~] 
on their own with a spoon — in fact, I did — but they may better serve you in a
grain bowl
[https://nl.nytimes.com/f/cooking/8U9lEuJLUIF47b4MOb1nUg~~/AAAAARA~/oachVbv4i_vSKsDbafZuTTB4kkmnbeIdztOb6K3t2nmROdjDPUeBYK5JOSMEsFA_ewmB2yhOZw--NkAkddn9pIBycYxfewZSwtGmKZaW7IdNEVC4rrI2jVGg0lXgw6MmrslrJgvVOfdG6V2IT8S1U3_GJd2FpHW60Oco4BHXbyTV8E385UVN_Bu70VEvuifjY3mU4EfacDBsN4UhXMyutkWs2hkVJjKw21sC80VWG9KV0tIV1yqzWBFsGpcNizyZHA-yJslY3bLnIgbc8ungY15DZCoPkPA_DjtNdHUsnS8RBthGYYXAJP8-QFMVfsgkIHR3otL_-HAKcocXD2u31OrA7HWFM9H6hkhbURO621L0WjFqcMsJnn0OdfXC7HOQrMLiiG1oKSh4ukw-x2OckQ~~]
. Or, as Kenji writes, “you could also stir together equal parts marinated
chickpeas and diced fresh cucumber with some slivered red onions and chopped
fresh dill, or massage some chopped kale with olive oil and a pinch of salt,
then toss in a big scoop of marinated chickpeas and some crumbled feta or
Cotija.” Quick, write that down.

column7: Ghostwriters are about to get super rich 💸
column9:
I have a brutal truth for you:

If you think ghostwriting is saturated (or there’s no demand),
you’re wrong.

Why?

Because in the last 10 years, we’ve seen a major shift in focus
from companies to individuals:

* People (read: customers) would rather work or buy from real
people over a faceless organization.
​
* So leaders need to invest more into scaling their messages
online and building audiences and communities around their
products and/or thinking.
​
* Which means demand for high-quality ghostwriters is only going
to go UP in the next 10 years.

​Entrepreneur.com (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/92uplrr8wpunhq73g4zu9hznq4333tw/m2h7h6u8drk2p4fl/aHR0cDovL2VudHJlcHJlbmV1ci5jb20v
) reports that 82% of people are more likely to trust a company
when its senior executives are active on social media.

With a stat like that, more and more executives are going to wake
up and realize they need a ghostwriter… FAST.

Dickie Bush 🚢-->

@dickiebush

I'm convinced the #1 skill for writers to build for the next 20
years is ghostwriting.

As things trend from companies to individuals, your
differentiator will be your ability to communicate and scale
other people's messages online. (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/92uplrr8wpunhq73g4zu9hznq4333tw/e0hph0u08x9mgzu7/aHR0cHM6Ly94LmNvbS9kaWNraWVidXNoL3N0YXR1cy8xODI0MTUxMjQyNjU1ODIyMDk1
)

)
​
But why can’t industry leaders, CEOs, business owners,
executives, etc. do this themselves?

For 4 big reasons (and why this is the perfect time for you to
become a Premium Ghostwriter and build a lucrative side hustle
for yourself):

*********************************************
Reason #1: They don’t have the time to write.
*********************************************

Imagine you’re the CEO of an EdTech startup and you’ve just
raised $23 million in your Series A funding round.

Flush with cash, you have 100 different priorities:

* Developing the product management strategy.
* Helping the business development team sell more.
* Dealing with Legal, HR, and other administrative issues.
* Ensuring the tech team has everything they need to fulfill your
vision for the product.

Etc, etc, etc.

With all of this on your plate, do you think you’d have the time
to write and publish your ideas on the internet? Unlikely. And
even if you did have the time to write, is writing how you get a
good ROI on your time as a CEO? Probably not.

This is where the ghostwriter comes in.

The CEO knows they need to be actively promoting their company to
attract new customers and make sure they’re making the case for
their next round of funding to a network of investors. In short,
they need to scale their message online.

Nicolas Cole 🚢-->

@Nicolascole77

This is the power of ghostwriting:

The world’s most experienced people don't have the time to share
what they know.

• Problem-solving frameworks
• Pattern recognition
• Expertise

Ghostwriters help them pass that knowledge on to others in a
scalable way. (
https://click.convertkit-mail.com/92uplrr8wpunhq73g4zu9hznq4333tw/owhkhwur2z3xm3hq/aHR0cHM6Ly94LmNvbS9OaWNvbGFzY29sZTc3L3N0YXR1cy8xNzkwMDg3NTE3OTM4NjMwNzI2
)

https://click.convertkit-mail.com/92uplrr8wpunhq73g4zu9hznq4333tw/owhkhwur2z3xm3hq/aHR0cHM6Ly94LmNvbS9OaWNvbGFzY29sZTc3L3N0YXR1cy8xNzkwMDg3NTE3OTM4NjMwNzI2
)
​
Ghostwriters are the people who have the time (and the skills) to
help them do this (without wasting hours slaving over a hot
keyboard every morning).

*************************************************************
Reason #2: They don’t like to write (or don’t want to learn).
*************************************************************

This is a simple one, but most people forget about it.

On top of not having the time to write, they don’t even have the
time to learn how to write. Or, worse still, they detested
writing at school so don’t want to do it. As a Premium
Ghostwriter, you know it takes time and reps to hone your skills
as a writer. Each platform and medium requires a unique set of
skills. Within those platforms, the nuances are always changing
too.

Industry leaders have no time to keep up with all of this, let
alone sit down and learn how to write.

Instead, as a ghostwriter, you come in and save them hours of
learning a skill they don’t even want to learn.

****************************************************
Reason #3: They need help clarifying their thinking.
****************************************************

As a writer, you’ll know that great writing just doesn’t appear
on the page.

Great writing comes from clear and careful thinking. So when
someone hires a ghostwriter, they want help in organizing their
thinking, stress-testing it, and making sure it’s robust.

As a ghostwriter, you bring numerous skills to the table:

* You’re able to organize and distill ideas down into their core
components.
​
* You’re able to structure writing to communicate complex ideas
in a simple manner.
​
* You’re able to approach a client’s thinking and stress test it
as their ideal reader or target audience and so enhance their
ideas in return.

And tons more.

Nicolas Cole 🚢-->

@Nicolascole77

The best ghostwriters don’t actually get paid to write.

They get paid to stress-test the client’s thinking.

• Ask thoughtful questions
• Present different perspectives
• Sharpen & refine ideas

This is what’s “valuable” to the client. (

)

)
​
In a world that’s increasingly competitive, it’s those with
clarity of thought who will stand out so having a ghostwriter to
do this for them is a win-win for the client.

*****************************************************************
Reason #4: They are stuck in old ways of working (and they need
your help!)
*****************************************************************

It’s a harsh truth, but most companies (and people leading those
companies) are terrible at building their digital presence.

* They use social media as a way to post announcements, not build
an audience or community.
​
* They have newsletter opt-ins on their website with a vague
promise to get “regular updates and goodies.”
​
* They have no understanding of why they need to move their
social audience to an owned platform (like an email list).

See a pattern here?

Most people are years behind where they need to be on their
messaging.

And as a Premium Ghostwriter, you can help them solve this
problem (in whichever area you’re an expert in). They know they
need help, they’re just waiting for the right person (i.e. you!)
to come along and help them!

“But Cole… what about the rise of AI? Won’t all of this be farmed
out to ChatGPT?”
-----------------------------------------------------------------

Ah, the classic AI excuse.

The truth is, most people who need to hire a ghostwriter don’t
have the time to tinker with ChatGPT prompts all day. They are
far too busy running their business or doing their day job.

column8: Everyone Says ‘Data Teams Should Drive Value’ But How?
column10:
View this post on the web at https://seattledataguy.substack.com/p/everyone-says-data-teams-should-drive

Hi, fellow future and current Data Leaders; Ben here 👋
Before diving into today’s newsletter, I want to take a moment to thank this issue’s sponsor, BMC [ https://substack.com/redirect/a19c6b66-bccb-465f-b3a3-bdf6bc40be73?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. Many data teams still spend too much time babysitting pipelines and stitching together scripts. Control-M helps automate that work, coordinating data workflows, triggering ML jobs, and syncing across cloud platforms, so teams can focus on analysis instead of maintenance. 
Check out their latest case study to see how it can simplify complex workflows [ https://substack.com/redirect/b9b2eb6c-4fae-4d41-a96b-71a79109c4ec?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
Now let’s jump into the article!
I’ve been think a lot about the fact that for many companies where the data team work ends, the business value only starts to begin. Even with a simple dashboard or model. You deliver the data product, then what?
Value is supposed to appear right?
After all that’s what the speaker said at a conference “data teams need to provide value” or some other cliche line. 
Of course data teams need to provide value. But how a team provides value is often left vague.
That’s where many leaders get stuck. They want their team to be “strategic” or “business-driven [ https://substack.com/redirect/91f0bd62-2701-4556-a717-35a800cd3b57?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ],” but they haven’t clearly defined what role their data team actually plays. 
A team tasked with building out a data warehouse [ https://substack.com/redirect/cbb5c09b-c649-406b-be89-cab8be688fb4?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] will provide value in a very different way than a team embedded with marketing to improve campaign ROI.
Over the years, I’ve seen multiple types of data teams. It can be tempting to think about data teams based on roles. That’s the analytics team, the data engineering team, the data infra team, etc. But I think it’s more important to think about the function you want your data team to have.
What are the goals, what is the business function it provides.
Sometimes data teams are strategic partners who connect business problems to data solutions. Others might be enabling other teams by being the platform builders who develop and maintain the data infrastructure and warehouse.
And in some organizations, the data team is just 1-2 people who have to do all of the above.
To figure out how your team provides value, you first need to understand the role it plays for the business.
Four Ways Data Teams Provide Value
A framework I enjoy when considering team types comes from Team Topologies: Organizing Business and Technology Teams for Fast Flow [ https://substack.com/redirect/ad1dd060-76a9-4a9b-b184-270303f158c5?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]. While the book is about technology teams broadly, its patterns apply neatly to data teams [ https://substack.com/redirect/f66bb760-2fb1-4565-96ce-7e8eca13ac78?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] too.
I’ve listed a few examples below.
Platform Teams
Platform teams are often a central infrastructure team that builds layers that everyone else can build on top of. For example a data engineering team that builds ingestion [ https://substack.com/redirect/cb4d30d2-ead8-4c85-8065-8111f6e29425?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] pipelines [ https://substack.com/redirect/4dd5e75d-3a14-4296-b6cd-8e054605a8a6?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] and manages the warehouse. Their value comes from enabling all other teams to access clean, reliable data. And if you’re in a large enough organization the data engineering team might be building on another platform team, the data infrastructure team.
It is important to note that a company only benefits from having a large investment in platform teams when there are enough analysts and end-users actually building tools and data products that the business uses.
Complicated Subsystem Teams
Sometimes companies need specialists. That’s where these teams come in. Think of a data science research team focused on building recommendation systems or a supply chain optimization model. Their value comes from delivering deep expertise that directly improves the business by either improving operating efficiencies or increasing revenue. 
Stream-Aligned Teams
These are domain-embedded teams that work directly alongside a specific business function, like Marketing, Operations, or Product, to deliver data products that drive day-to-day decisions. For example, a marketing analytics team embedded within the growth organization that builds dashboards [ https://substack.com/redirect/42a438c7-9c38-4575-8a46-3426bf1e7a21?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], models, and experiments to directly influence campaign spend and customer acquisition.
Their value comes from proximity, being close enough to the business to understand context, move quickly, and measure impact. They turn data into decisions without layers of translation between business and data teams.
Enabling Teams
This would be some form of Data Enablement Team within a larger analytics organization. They don’t own production pipelines or dashboards, instead, they help other teams become more capable with data. At least, how it’s described in the book is a heavy focus on pure enablement. Now this is the one I might disagree with a bit in terms of where I see the value. I’d view this team as one that can connect business problems with data solutions. They can span the entire stack.
SeattleDataGuy’s Newsletter is a reader-supported publication. To receive new posts and support my work, consider becoming a free or paid subscriber.
Defining Your Data Team’s Role and Vision
These categories don’t capture every possible type of data team, but they offer a useful starting point. They help data and business leaders [ https://substack.com/redirect/37523856-e206-4934-b8b4-061b43f7c543?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ] clarify how different teams create value and what role each should play within the organization.
Once you’ve identified where your team fits, the next step is to define what success looks like for that role, both for the business and within the data organization.
Ask questions like:
What outcomes is this team accountable for?
How does it interact with other teams?
What capabilities or resources does it need to deliver impact?
How will we measure progress beyond technical metrics?
>From there, you can start shaping a clear vision and the pillars your data organization will stand on. This should focus less on the motions or daily activities and more the outcomes you want your team to drive.
Making This Framework Actionable
Understanding your team type is only step one. Once you know it, you can start making decisions on where you can drive value.
Set Expectations With Leadership
I’ve seen many data teams get trapped as catch-alls. Automation, AI, data engineer, analytics, enabling, platform, etc.
In some cases, well, when you’re a team of one  [ https://substack.com/redirect/864301d2-eb3c-4a02-a35a-603f643e447d?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]you’ll have to do it all. But there is only so much any team can get done and the more you try to increase that scope, the more likely you’ll start putting out bad work.
Or, on the flip side, you’ll succeed and then be stuck maintaining work that doesn’t drive much impact but two people say they really need.
So as you’re setting expectations, here are some tips:
Don’t promise “strategic insights” if you’re really resourced as a platform team
Frame success in terms of the value your team type is best positioned to provide
Prioritize the Right Work
Setting expectations makes it easier to prioritize the right work, because some work that comes your way will clearly not be best suited for your team. If your team is built up with DevOps and platform engineers, you won’t be as effective building front-end dashboards [ https://substack.com/redirect/7f0aa51a-81ec-473b-b5ad-8994fd8d9289?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ].
For example:
Platform teams should focus on reliability and scalability, not ad-hoc requests
Stream-aligned teams should bias toward speed and responsiveness
This is of course assuming your company is large enough to break down your data teams into these specialities.
Communicate Value in Business Terms
As someone who has worked on a platform team, it can be difficult to communicate your value. Often your work enables other teams to deliver value directly to the business. But you rarely get the credit unless you clearly tie it to what those teams are doing.
Here are some examples of how each type of data team might communicate their value:
Enabling team: “We helped the sales org standardize KPIs, reducing weekly reporting time by 20 hours”
Platform team: “We improved data freshness from 24 hours to near real-time [ https://substack.com/redirect/0d953b0b-7846-49ad-b270-a7aef1ca4fa4?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ], allowing the operations team to respond to issues”
Complicated subsystem team: “Our demand forecast reduced stockouts by 15%, saving $5M.”
Stream-aligned team: “Our campaign ROI dashboard helped reallocate budget, increasing efficiency by 12%.”
Closing Thought
In some organizations a data team is two people who spend half their time on analytics and the other half on IT workflows. While larger and more data-critical organizations have teams broken down into specific types. 
Regardless, if you’re not careful all these teams can start to lose their purpose. In some cases they become catch-alls and in others they become so divorced from the business that they don’t even drive value any more. 
That’s why it’s important to start with a general why. Why does your team exist and what is it that you do for the business.
As always, thanks for reading.
Upcoming Data Events
Seattle Happy Hour At The Rhein Haus With BMC [ https://substack.com/redirect/4fe0e33c-dbf1-4166-876f-b702a061e3df?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ](I’ll Be There!)
Airflow Summit 2025(I’ll be there!) [ https://substack.com/redirect/05035720-daf7-4da1-b865-38c0cc319849?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Streaming Kafka Data into MotherDuck with Estuary Flow [ https://substack.com/redirect/f45118c0-ceaf-43df-8871-4d5fc5630055?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
Articles Worth Reading
There are thousands of new articles posted daily all over the web! I have spent a lot of time sifting through some of these articles as well as TechCrunch and companies tech blog and wanted to share some of my favorites!
The Knowledge Architect’s Playbook: The Pedantic Medallion
By Ramona C. Truta  
Let’s be honest with each other. Is our expertise a bridge, or is it a wall?
In our industries, we are paid for what we know. But we build value only when that knowledge is shared and understood. Too often, we build walls. We hide behind jargon, complex diagrams, and esoteric tools, not to create clarity, but to signal our own intelligence. We speak from a level we believe proves our worth, forgetting that the goal of communication is not to broadcast our own brilliance, but to build a shared reality with others.
Read More Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/f06fb234-e7c6-4017-8d05-47ef2f3afcf7?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
The “D” In Data Stands For Discipline
A seasoned data leader once told me something that stuck: the d in data stands for discipline.
Now to be clear, pretty much every field requires discipline.
But we often focus on the exciting parts of data work in articles.
Not the tedious, repetitive, mundane, just doing the right thing type work.
Read More Here [ https://substack.com/redirect/f37abdd1-53f4-4f01-bbc0-f24479d54b83?j=eyJ1IjoiNTFkc2s3In0.TG_s5GaRal_EYLFDF-UYKHL5eEiDcX8TdL6-5nynlYA ]
End Of Day 196

There's SO MUCH exciting stuff happening here at ClickFunnels, we can hardly
contain our excitement...



We've been working overtime to make sure ClickFunnels has every single tool you
need to succeed online. (Keep reading to see the newest integration - it's a
game-changer!) But with so many powerful features packed in, it can be a little
overwhelming trying to keep up with it all.



Don't worry, we've got your back!

Introducing Our New Newsletter Format

Instead of hitting you with everything all at once, each week we're going to
focus on what's new, what's important, and shine a spotlight on ONE key feature 
you might not know about yet.



Because here's the thing... we've got 16 (yes, SIXTEEN!) distinct applications
integrated into ClickFunnels. Each one is a fully capable business solution all
on its own. And for many companies, just one of these features is their entire
business. But with ClickFunnels, you get access to ALL of them, no matter what
plan you're on. That's what we call "all in one"!



[https://d15k2d11r6t6rl.cloudfront.net/public/users/Integrators/f1027de7-2038-4cb2-b32d-e3b0cf3875c1/workspace-10/App_Store_Newsletter_Feature.png]
[https://www.clickfunnels.com/_tracking/email_click/broadcast/eXDmWO/dBkOMyR/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2xpY2tmdW5uZWxzLmNvbT91dG1fc291cmNlPWNmX2NvbW1zJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPWNsaWNrZnVubmVscyZ1dG1fdGVybT1tYWluX2NvbnRlbnQmdXRtX2NvbnRlbnQ9bmV3c2xldHRlcl84NQ%3D%3D]
Have You Seen the New App Page?

Now, you might be so busy building funnels that you haven't even noticed, but we
recently launched the new App Page. Here, you can see all the different features
you have available, and what you have installed. (Think of the App Store on your
phone.) This keeps your dashboard clean and uncluttered while you're building.



Oh... and we've got some BiG things in the works for the App Page. So make sure
you keep an eye on this newsletter each week to stay up to date. ;)



[https://d15k2d11r6t6rl.cloudfront.net/public/users/Integrators/f1027de7-2038-4cb2-b32d-e3b0cf3875c1/workspace-10/Message_Hub_Newsletter_Feature.png]
[https://www.clickfunnels.com/_tracking/email_click/broadcast/eXDmWO/dBkOMyR/aHR0cHM6Ly9jbGtmdW5sLmNvbS9NZXNzYWdlSHVi]
Your One-Stop-Shop For Customer Messaging and Support In ClickFunnels!

Feature Spotlight: MessageHub

Maybe you're not as excited about customer support and messaging as we are...



But you SHOULD be! Because this often makes the difference between a massively
successful business, and one that fails.



That's why this week, we want to introduce you to our MessageHub app. MessageHub
is a complete customer support and messaging platform, and it's built right into
ClickFunnels. (And is in your account, no matter what plan you're on.)



Inside, you can manage all your customer interactions from one place, respond to
customers lightning fast, and never miss an important message again. It's text,
email, AND social media messaging in one simple interface. No more jumping
between a million different platforms to chat with your customers and prospects!



This makes your life wayyy EASIER and keeps your customers happy.

Plus, it helps you keep the conversation going with follow-ups, reminders, and
personalized offers, ensuring your customers feel valued throughout their
journey with you.



Even better? You can set up automated workflows to handle responses and actions
based on different communication triggers. This means fast and effective
interactions, and frees you up from those tedious manual tasks.



In short, MessageHub helps you build amazing relationships, boost customer
satisfaction, and increase conversion rates! A win-win-win.

Our Co-Founder, Todd Dickerson, filmed a new video to show you the benefits of
MessageHub. You can check it out here
[https://www.clickfunnels.com/_tracking/email_click/broadcast/eXDmWO/dBkOMyR/aHR0cHM6Ly9jbGtmdW5sLmNvbS9NZXNzYWdlSHVi]
, then head over to the App Page to install and explore MessageHub for yourself.
We're sure you're going to love it!



[https://d15k2d11r6t6rl.cloudfront.net/public/users/Integrators/f1027de7-2038-4cb2-b32d-e3b0cf3875c1/workspace-10/Zendrop_Newsletter_Feature.png]
[https://www.clickfunnels.com/_tracking/email_click/broadcast/eXDmWO/dBkOMyR/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2xpY2tmdW5uZWxzLmNvbS96ZW5kcm9wP3V0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y2ZfY29tbXMmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249emVuZHJvcCZ1dG1fdGVybT1tYWluX2NvbnRlbnQmdXRtX2NvbnRlbnQ9bmV3c2xldHRlcl84NQ%3D%3D]In Case You Missed The Big Reveal:

Feature Spotlight: Zendrop Integration

Maybe you were soaking up the sun on vacation, knee-deep in a launch, or just
missed all the hoopla...



But a few weeks back, we announced a feature that so many #FunnelHackers have
been waiting for. And we wanted to give you a quick rundown of this highly
requested feature we announced a few weeks back - the Zendrop integration.



With ClickFunnels + Zendrop, you get instant access to millions of ready-to-ship
products so you can start selling immediately. No need to create a product,
manage inventory, or handle fulfillment. Zendrop takes care of shipping and
logistics, allowing you to focus on growing your business.



Access Millions of Products: With a single click, connect your ClickFunnels
account to Zendrop and explore a directory of over ONE MILLION ready-to-sell
products across various niches.



Effortless Import and Customization: Select products you want to sell, customize
descriptions, images, and variants, and import them directly into your
ClickFunnels workspace.



Full Dropshipping Solution: Zendrop handles all shipping and fulfillment, so you
can concentrate on scaling your business without worrying about logistics.



Want more details? Check out the full Zendrop announcement video
[https://www.clickfunnels.com/_tracking/email_click/broadcast/eXDmWO/dBkOMyR/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2xpY2tmdW5uZWxzLmNvbS96ZW5kcm9wP3V0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y2ZfY29tbXMmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249emVuZHJvcCZ1dG1fdGVybT1tYWluX2NvbnRlbnQmdXRtX2NvbnRlbnQ9bmV3c2xldHRlcl84NQ%3D%3D] 
here.

Always Getting Better, Week After Week

We're 100% committed to making ClickFunnels better each and every week. Along

YOUR feedback.



Thank you for being part of the ClickFunnels family. Helping you achieve your

IT!





To your success,



- The ClickFunnels Team

Yesterday, we launched Low-Ticket Launchpad (

Every single digital product we’ve launched over the last 5 years

--------------------------
But we won’t sugarcoat it:
--------------------------

This takes work.

We’ve made hundreds of embarrassing mistakes and wasted thousands
of hours figuring this out through painful trial and error.

Selling a digital product isn’t some “get rich quick
scheme”—you’ll need to roll up your sleeves, go through each

product.

​
But here’s the magic of investing in education like this:

***************************************************
You invest $350 ONCE to sell $350 products FOREVER.
***************************************************

You’re paying a tiny fraction of your earning potential now in
return for almost unlimited upside:

​

And the best part?

You skip the 5-year learning curve we’ve been through.

Instead of having to build your digital product from scratch, you

to master.

“But Dickie… Cole.. haven’t you guys said selling services is the

-----------------------------------------------------------------

Absolutely! And we stand by that.

But here’s the ceiling you hit when you ONLY sell services:

You’re still trading hours for dollars—and the brutal truth is

-----------------------------------------------------------------

Sure, you could build an agency, but that means hiring employees,
managing people, and dealing with all the other headaches that

And no matter how efficient you get, there’s always a limit

You’re selling “digital air”—once created, your cost to deliver

Well, don’t worry. This is actually a GOOD thing.

You’re starting with a blank page. You can start writing online

The sudden rise of “vibe coding”—non-programmers using savvy
prompting to tease code out of LLMs—has sparked a revolution far
beyond computer screens.      Brilliant Newsletter   The sudden
rise of “vibe coding”—non-programmers using savvy prompting to
tease code out of LLMs—has sparked a revolution far beyond
computer screens. Now, just about any activity can be tackled
simply by harnessing the power of vibes.

“Vibe flying” was the first trend to take off (and, no surprise,
first to crash). Then there was the rise of “vibe welding,”
quickly followed by an uptick in “vibe firefighting.” Meanwhile,
the number of new “vibe surgeons” and “vibe dentists” has been
strangely equal to the number of new “real lawyers.”

Feel free to run a vibe check (and a check of today’s
date) before believing any of that—but the truth is that
LLM-assisted coding is here to stay. And while AI alone won’t
turn newbies into hackers—knowing just a few powerful concepts
can give your vibes a serious supercharge.

In just a few minutes a day—about the time it takes to write a
LLM prompt—you can learn things like how to harness the power of
functions. Next thing you know, you’ll be building modular,
scalable programs. How’s that for good vibes?

April Puzzle
------------

Just in time for April Fools’ Day, the social media site
Scrollr has added an AI fact-checking feature. Initially, 2/3 of
posts are tagged “Real” and 1/3 “Prank” by human reviewers. The
AI fact-checker works like so: 3/4 of the time it flips a post’s
tag from “Real” to “Prank” or vice versa, and 1/4 of the time it
decides no action is needed, which locks the post’s tag forever.
If the tag gets flipped, the AI fact-checker does another review.

What is the probability a post will end up tagged “Real”?

Bonus: Scrollr is considering capping the number of revisions a
post’s tag can receive. What should Scrollr set as the cap in
order to get the number of “Real” and “Prank” posts as close as
possible?

Submit answer ( https://click.brilliant.org/f/a/pwNdl4CW5964MWNAEm7S2A~~/AAQRxRA~/NrZAcAIy2cVNrCq849P7kYxutFAER2ZvA7xgv_k2CURnMIYaARdC5vnuK5CiyY2t1B4XJbTSqAOKa1q8O5dPVxucmqkpRF5FjuHYGK6wQebNiICvmgZTDqSzCWson1K9 )
We’ll randomly choose one correct respondent to each puzzle for a
shout-out in next month’s email.

---------------------

puzzles and got a tight approximation for the bonus puzzle.

The key to figuring out which word had the advantage was
thinking about how their shared subword (“TALE”) allowed STALE to
steal victories out from under TALES. For more details, see this
month’s solution, which includes Charlie’s slick argument.

Hi Candace Grant,

The year is off to a fast start, with some groundbreaking new modelsshaking assumptions of what's possible. We're thrilled to highlight some ofthe new models you can find on the Kaggle Model Hub here in 2025!






Mistral Small 3
Publisher: Mistral
Mistral Small 3 is the latest open-weight model in the sub-70B category,
designed for efficiency and versatility. Well-suited for general-purpose
conversational AI, robotics, and low-latency applications, it delivers
powerful performance in a compact size.






DeepSeek R-1
Publisher: DeepSeek
DeepSeek-R1 demonstrates advanced reasoning capabilities with
emergent behaviors powered by reinforcement learning alone. By
incorporating cold-start data, it addresses repetition and enhances
performance across tasks.






MobileLLM
Publisher: Meta
MobileLLM is a family of efficient sub-billion parameter models for
mobile devices, using embedding sharing and grouped-query
attention for top-tier chat and API performance. Models range
from 125M to 1.5B, outperforming prior benchmarks.






KaLM Embedding
Publisher: HITsz-Text Machine Group
KaLM-Embedding, a series of embedding models adapted from
auto-regressive LLMs with superior training data. Based on
Qwen/Qwen2-0.5B, the mini version boasts extensive
pre-training and fine-tuning.






ModernBERT
Publisher: Answer.AI
ModernBERT is a state-of-the-art encoder-only model family,
handling up to 8,192 tokens. Optimized for long-context tasks in
text and code. It uses Rotary Positional Embeddings and
Local-Global Attention for efficiency.





We can't wait to see what you build!

Brenda Flynn

Your entrepreneur journey isn’t what you think it is... Hey Candace,

It’s tempting to think your entrepreneur journey is unique. When you’re so close
to your own journey, it can be hard to get perspective.

However, in thinking it’s unique and different from everyone else’s, you get
caught up in the details and miss the big picture.

We’ve worked with thousands of entrepreneurs and interviewed thousands more
across a wide range of industries. What we’ve discovered is the entrepreneur
journey is a lot more predictable across their businesses than it is unique.

There are certain problems and frustrations that come along at a very
predictable time, and there are also strategies you can deploy to overcome them
if you know the journey ahead of you.

Here’s what it looks like:

 1. Start-up - Pre-revenue or early stage business, testing out ideas in the
    market, enthusiasm but little track record or results.
    
    
 2. Wilderness - Struggling solopreneur or small team, trading time for money,
    no productized offering, juggling multiple roles, hand to mouth survival,
    broad value proposition - nothing really unique about their business from
    the market’s perspective.
    
 3. Lifestyle - A team of 3 - 12 people, less hours, more freedom, revenue high
    6 to early 7 figures, good profit. Lots of digital and IP assets, being
    leveraged by the people in the business. Unique, differentiated and in
    demand.
    
    
 4. The Desert - Too big to be a small business, and too small to be a big
    business. Heavy investment in infrastructure and long-term investment
    cycles, high-risk, no cash, people complexity and constantly starved of
    cash, low profitability. High stakes, high stress.
    
    
 5. Performance - Team of 40+ people, EBITDA close to or above $1M. Leadership
    team running the business. Not founder reliant. Steady growth, high
    valuation, investable, great team culture, profitable again. 
    
    
 6. (BONUS) Unicorn ⁠- A team of 250+ people with ultra-high revenue per person
    that happened to be at the right place and time with the right opportunity
    (eg. software, ecommerce, blockchain)⁠

Hey friends,

This week, my team flew into Hong Kong for our quarterly offsite
🥳 We pulled up the Notion doc from January where we’d excitedly
mapped out 18 quests for Q1, and then checked what we actually
completed.

We finished 4. Just 4 out of 18. That’s a grand total of 22%.

Not great.

Quick sidebar - we call our goals “quests” because it just sounds
more fun and slightly less corporate. It adds a bit of a
Feel-Good vibe to what would otherwise be a dry planning
document. But still… 4 out of 18 quests?

At first, it felt a bit embarrassing. We had such a clear plan.
What happened?

But then I remembered something from Traction (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/27u74ok3xrboh8gz52nh3hgl55w44hg/vqh3hmuoxw3k53tw/aHR0cHM6Ly9nZW5pLnVzL1A5blNxRW0=
) by Gino Wickman (honestly one of the most useful business books
I’ve ever read). Apparently, when companies do structured
goal-setting for the first time, they typically only hit around
30% of their targets. Which, now that I think about it, makes us…
almost average?

Still. It stings. But also, it makes total sense. The reason is
super simple: we all just set too many goals.

Especially when we’ve got a growing team. It’s so tempting to
think: “Well, we’ve got 18 people, so surely we can do 18
things.” One quest per person. Perfectly logical, right?

Except, that’s not really how it works.

More people doesn’t mean more output. It means more coordination,
more communication, more updates, more ambiguity… And that
translates into more meetings, more Slack threads, more Loom
videos to watch, and more decisions that need to be made before
anything actually ships.

Every new goal introduces a hidden tax: someone has to define it,
track it, push it forward, check in on progress, loop others in,
unblock issues… and before you know it, half your time is spent
talking about work rather than doing the work.

This happens in my personal life, too. The more goals I set, the
less likely I am to complete any of them. I tell myself, “It’s
fine, I’ll just work on these in parallel.” But what ends up
happening is everything moves forward by 10%, and nothing ever
quite finishes.

The same principle shows up at the team level. When we took a
closer look at our Q1 quests, we realised that for most of them,
we’d made decent progress. A lot of them were around 60–80% done.
But as Traction puts it: “90% done is still not done.” And once
we see that, it’s hard to unsee.

So this quarter, we’re changing the way we approach things.

We’ve got three main departments (Content, Software, and
Courses), and in the spirit of boiling each department’s progress
down to one measurable goal, we decided to go with the following
numbers:

* For Content: Grow the email list
* For Software: Increase monthly recurring revenue
* For Courses: Grow revenue

And under each of those goals, we’re only allowing ourselves up
to three major projects. No more trying to spin nine different
plates at once. Just three key things, scoped tightly enough that
we can actually finish them within the quarter.

It’s surprisingly hard to do. There are so many exciting ideas
floating around—product updates we could build, content
experiments we could try, partnerships we could explore. But this
new system forces us to ask: “Of all the things we could do…
what’s the one thing that would move the needle most
meaningfully?”

If we’re honest, we already know what the big levers are. The
hard part is committing to them. Saying “no” to all the other
shiny ideas that might feel urgent or important in the moment.

22% completion isn’t something to be proud of. But I actually
think it’s a really valuable data point. It’s a reminder that
it’s easy to get distracted by moving in many different
directions instead of focusing on what would make the most
meaningful progress to the business.

We even talk about it repeatedly in LifeOS (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/27u74ok3xrboh8gz52nh3hgl55w44hg/m2h7h6u3g40nrnhl/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2xpZmVvcz91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249YXByaWw0JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1saWZlbm90ZXM=
), including in the Spring Reset that we hosted last Saturday.
Funnily enough, we don’t follow our own advice. It’s a lesson we
keep having to relearn: the more goals we set, the less likely we
are to achieve any of them.

Have a great week!

Ali xx

column7: 📈 Curate your “taste” into mouth-watering hooks [Weekly Viral Templates]
column9:
Welcome back to Weekly Viral Templates—an exclusive perk for
Typeshare Pro users. Each week, we break down 3 pieces of content
that went viral (Tweet, Thread, Atomic Essay, LinkedIn post,
etc.) and explain why they worked. Then, we turn them into a
Typeshare Template you can immediately put into practice.

Hey there!

This week’s theme is Curation, and we have 3 exciting hooks to
break down for you:

* Hook #1: The “People’s Choice”
* Hook #2: The “Best Threads”
* Hook #3: The “Man Behind The Curtain”

​

**********************************************
Viral Breakdown #1: The “People’s Choice” Hook
**********************************************

(
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/r8urzel34pi9urkqnlh2hd684z66s7/7qh7h8hoke52olfz/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9kaWNraWVidXNoL3N0YXR1cy8xNjA2NjYwNzUwMTUxMzkzMjgx
)​
​Link To Thread (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/r8urzel34pi9urkqnlh2hd684z66s7/7qh7h8hoke52olfz/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9kaWNraWVidXNoL3N0YXR1cy8xNjA2NjYwNzUwMTUxMzkzMjgx
)​

Let’s break down all the different pieces working in this hook:

* Success Envy: “I asked 300k people…” Everyone wants to know
what others are doing to succeed, and Dickie leverages the power
(and size) of his audience to crowdsource a “best of” list that
appeal to a broad audience. The chances a reader will find
something new and of interest in this thread are extremely high.
Books, Podcasts, Lessons, etc. are all universal things anyone
and everyone would love for you to curate for them.
​
* Taste Filter: “Then, I spent hours…Here’s the recap” Dickie
draws on his credibility and taste by calling out the significant
effort and time he puts into distilling responses of an audience
of 300K. The reader wants to know not just what his audience
recommends, but also what Dickie selected. And if you made a
suggestion, you are going to click to see if your recommendation
made the list. Triple whammy!

**************************************************
Viral Typeshare Template #1: The “People’s Choice”
**************************************************

Here’s the recap of each one:

Then I spent {Time} compiling answers to create the Best of
{Time} Curation.

I asked {Number} people for their favorite things of {Time
Period}
​
{Category 1}
{Category 2}
{Category 3}
{Category 4}
{Category 5}
​
Then I spent {Time} compiling answers to create the Best of
{Time} Curation.
​
Here's the recap of each one:

Then I spent {Time} compiling answers to create the Best of
{Time} Curation.

​Click here to open this Template in your drafts inside
Typeshare. (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/r8urzel34pi9urkqnlh2hd684z66s7/p8heh9hz3eowzwaq/aHR0cHM6Ly90eXBlc2hhcmUuY28vdGVtcGxhdGVzL3BhY2tzL3Rhc3RlLW1ha2Vycy10b29sa2l0
)​

*******************************************
Viral Breakdown #2: The “Best Threads” Hook
*******************************************

(
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/r8urzel34pi9urkqnlh2hd684z66s7/x0hph6hwrm0vw5t5/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9OaWNvbGFzY29sZTc3L3N0YXR1cy8xNTQxNzgzNTEyNTU4MzA1Mjgx
)​
​Link To Thread (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/r8urzel34pi9urkqnlh2hd684z66s7/x0hph6hwrm0vw5t5/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9OaWNvbGFzY29sZTc3L3N0YXR1cy8xNTQxNzgzNTEyNTU4MzA1Mjgx
)​

Let’s break down all the different pieces working in this hook:

* Filtered Opinion: “The 8 best storytelling..” Cole use a number
to create a sense of organization and clarity, making it easy for
readers to follow along and setting expectations for the content.
It’s not just 8, it’s the 8 best. There are tens of thousands of
threads that hit Twitter every single day and these are the ones
that storytellers should pay attention to as selected by a
credible author with good taste.
​
* Challenging Task: Stories are an art and are very hard to
execute on Twitter. Cole offers a helpful distillation to make it
easy for the reader to learn from the best.

***********************************************
Viral Typeshare Template #2: The “Best Threads”
***********************************************

The {Number} best {Topic} threads on Twitter:
​Click here to open this Template in your drafts inside
Typeshare. (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/r8urzel34pi9urkqnlh2hd684z66s7/p8heh9hz3eowzwaq/aHR0cHM6Ly90eXBlc2hhcmUuY28vdGVtcGxhdGVzL3BhY2tzL3Rhc3RlLW1ha2Vycy10b29sa2l0
)​

*****************************************************
Viral Breakdown #3: The “Man Behind The Curtain” Hook
*****************************************************

(
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/r8urzel34pi9urkqnlh2hd684z66s7/6qheh8h7k4e879uo/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9TaGFuZV9fX01hcnRpbi9zdGF0dXMvMTU5Mzk5NTcyMjI0NzkyMTY2NT9zPTIw
)​
​Link To Thread (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/r8urzel34pi9urkqnlh2hd684z66s7/kkhmh6hldpv0lofl/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9TaGFuZV9fX01hcnRpbi9zdGF0dXMvMTU5Mzk5NTcyMjI0NzkyMTY2NQ==
)​

Let’s break down all the different pieces working in this hook:

* Well-Known Names: “Michael Jordan…” By starting with the names
of legendary athletes, the hook immediately captures the reader's
attention—even if you’re not a basketball fan.
​
* Mysterious Connection: “3 killers… but 1 man behind the
curtain.” Shane creates intrigue by highlighting what the
basketball players are known for and then, in contrast, suggests
there's a hidden force connecting these successful athletes
further setting the hook.
​
* Curated Lessons: “I spent hours…7 key lessons…” Shane outlines
the key lessons to be learned and entices readers with 3 valuable
takeaways for reading.

*********************************************************
Viral Typeshare Template #3: The “Man Behind The Curtain”
*********************************************************

{Well-Known Person 1}, {Well-Known Person 2}, {Well-Known Person
3}
​
3 {Descriptive Adjective They Are All Known For}
​
But 1 {Gender} behind the curtain.
​
{Name the Mystery Person}
​
I spent {Time} studying their work.
​
Here are the {Number} key lessons for {Outcome 1}, {Outcome 2}, &
{Outcome 3}
​Click here to open this Template in your drafts inside
Typeshare. (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/r8urzel34pi9urkqnlh2hd684z66s7/p8heh9hz3eowzwaq/aHR0cHM6Ly90eXBlc2hhcmUuY28vdGVtcGxhdGVzL3BhY2tzL3Rhc3RlLW1ha2Vycy10b29sa2l0
)​

That’s it for the Taste Makers Toolkit!

Sincerely,

Typeshare

Nicolas Cole, Dickie Bush, and Sam
Shore

Our goal has always been to deliver the value you deserve regardless of whether you buy or sell on Mercari. With that in mind and after carefully considering your feedback, we have an important update: We’re rolling out a new fee structure starting on January 6, 2025.

When we introduced our current fee structure in March, our aim was to make selling more accessible to sellers. However, we realized this structure wasn’t helping sellers sell more and ultimately negatively impacted Mercari and our community by reducing overall transactions on the marketplace. The new fee structure addresses these concerns. Our new fee structure: We’re reintroducing a selling fee and lowering the buyer fee. This new fee structure aligns the benefits you receive with the fees you pay. For Sellers A flat 10% selling fee applies to item price and buyer-paid shipping Free ACH direct deposits for successful withdrawals. A $2 fee applies only for rejected deposits. Limit to one direct deposit per day. For more information on Seller Protection, please see
